pullRequest.body:
For $R$-modules $M$ and $D$ where $D$ is injective, we can consider the dual module $M^\star := \mathrm{Hom}_R(M, D)$. 
$(\cdot^\star)$ can define a contravariant functor $R$-mod to $R$-mod by $L \mapsto L^\star$ where $L^\star f = f \circ L$ where $L \in \mathrm{Hom}_R(M, N)$ and $f \in N^\star$. This functor sends monomorphisms to epimorphisms.

For an abelian group $A$, it is useful to consider its character module in the unit rational circle. This construction appears in proof of enough-injectiveness of groups and it can be shown that a module is flat if and only if its character module is injective, [reference](https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/canadian-mathematical-bulletin/article/module-is-flat-if-and-only-if-its-character-module-is-injective/8D9669F28AC4DE35A1D65EA864F9B5DE). Hence we use Baer to relate ideals. 

Also refactored enough-injectiveness of abelian groups. The refactor is not a separated PR because construction of character module needs some result from `GroupCat/Injective.lean` file.

Why do you need `uR` here? You want a universe >= uR for injectivity to work? And why do you need to write `CharacterModule.{uR, uM, uD}` everywhere?

I'm puzzled by how the current state of this PR (and #8906) departed from this original commit. In this commit, the domain M is a (R,Z)-bimodule and the codomain `AddCircle (1 : â„š)` is only a Z-module, and the R-action on `CharacterModule M` is on the domain (of course). As the PR currently stands, both the domain and the codomain are R-modules and there isn't a second ring, and you're using LinearMap.module to define the R-module structure on `CharacterModule R M D`, which acts on the codomain (but it's equivalent to acting on the domain, because you consider R-linear maps not Z-linear maps).

Are you sure the current definition can still help you prove things about flatness? Do you have it in some branch? I'd be curious to see. My suspicion is that Matlis duality doesn't fit in the same framework as what you want to do.

We can still force the proof to work because `M â†’â‚—[â„¤] â„š â§¸ â„¤` is still an `R`-module, but `CharcterModule.(un)curry, cong, homEquiv` cannot be used directly because they will only be `â„¤`-linear, but since they are still true, we can just make another copy of these constructions and use `CharacterModule.unitRationalCircle.(un)curry, cong, homEquiv` which are `R`-linear to prove injectiveness.
